---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import Card from '../components/Card.astro';
import ServiceCard from '../components/ServiceCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Methods - Chris Krough"
  description="Methods for building with agents: harness engineering, evaluation, multi-instance coordination, MCP fluency. Public artifacts included."
>
  <Hero
    headline="Methods"
    subheadline="How I build with agents in production. Harness engineering, evaluation, multi-instance coordination. Each section links to a public artifact."
  />

  <!-- §2 Harness engineering -->
  <section class="section-spacing bg-foundation-deep">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-4">Harness engineering</h2>
        <p class="text-base text-muted mb-8 max-w-3xl">
          Patterns for steering the agentic harness for consistent reliable results: lifecycle hooks, scoped subagents, and portable skills.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <ServiceCard
            title="Hooks"
            description="Lifecycle hooks (PreToolUse, PostToolUse, PostCompact) run in production to enforce guardrails, route follow-up work, and preserve context across long sessions."
            items={[
              'PreToolUse guards reject unsafe edits before they reach the filesystem.',
              'PostToolUse reminders route follow-up work to the right skill.',
              'PostCompact restores context so long-running sessions stay coherent.',
            ]}
          />

          <ServiceCard
            title="Named subagents with tool-scope constraints"
            description="Subagents specialize by responsibility, each with a tool allowlist scoped to the role."
            items={[
              'Correctness: a role cannot reach for a tool outside its mandate.',
              'Speed: narrower tool surfaces produce faster, more focused decisions.',
              'Auditability: role boundaries are explicit in configuration.',
            ]}
          />

          <ServiceCard
            title="Plugins conforming to the agentskills.io specification"
            description="Skills are authored to the agentskills.io specification. They remain portable and harness-independent. Published through Backchain."
          >
            <ul class="space-y-2 mt-2">
              <li class="text-base text-muted flex items-start">
                <span class="text-accent mr-2 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                <span>
                  <a href="https://github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins</a>
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="text-base text-muted flex items-start">
                <span class="text-accent mr-2 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
                <span>
                  <a href="https://agentskills.io/specification" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">agentskills.io specification</a>
                </span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </ServiceCard>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- §3 Context and model budgeting -->
  <section class="section-spacing">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-4">Context and model budgeting</h2>
        <p class="text-base text-muted mb-8 max-w-3xl">
          Two knobs control efficiency: which model runs the work, and what context loads before it starts.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <ServiceCard
            title="Context stacking across configuration roots"
            description="Three configuration layers compose at runtime. User root (~/.claude) holds broadly useful skills and plugins, kept lean by disabling most by default. A professional-domain root holds work references, standards, and voice guides. Project roots (.claude, CLAUDE.md) hold repo-specific rules. claude --add-dir stacks the domain onto a project without polluting either context. --plugin-dir extends the pattern to plugins."
            items={[
              'Scoped installs: skills enabled per project rather than globally.',
              'Selective enable-by-default: expensive context loads only when needed.',
              'Shared references: professional standards reused across projects without duplication.',
            ]}
          />

          <ServiceCard
            title="Rules, standards, references"
            description="Rules in .claude/rules/ auto-load on session start. They stay thin and encode project conventions: file naming, git protocol, issue tracking, voice. Companion material in .claude/standards/ and reference/ loads only when a skill calls for it. Context stays compact until depth matters."
            items={[
              'Rules: auto-loaded conventions, one topic per file.',
              'Standards: full registries, specs, and tables loaded on demand.',
              'References: external URL lists and vocabulary pulled by skills when relevant.',
            ]}
          />

          <ServiceCard
            title="Model-tier routing"
            description="Skills and subagents specify the model appropriate to the role. Fast cheap models run triage, summarization, and shallow lookups. Advanced models run architecture, review, and planning. Cost tracks complexity."
            items={[
              'Triage and routing: fast tier.',
              'Implementation and editing: mid tier.',
              'Architecture and review: advanced tier.',
            ]}
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- §4 Evaluation practice -->
  <section class="section-spacing bg-foundation-deep">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-4">Evaluation practice</h2>
        <p class="text-base text-muted mb-8 max-w-3xl">
          Prompt-defined skills have no ground truth. Reproducible evaluation distinguishes real quality changes from run-to-run variance.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <ServiceCard
            title="Methods"
            description="Every skill change is graded against a fixed rubric in a reproducible harness."
            items={[
              'Assertion-based LLM-as-judge grading against per-criterion rubrics.',
              'Clean-room isolation via claude --bare prevents state leakage between trials.',
              'promptfoo in CI for regression across releases.',
            ]}
          />

          <Card variant="default">
            <h3 class="text-h3 font-heading font-medium text-structure mb-3">Worked example: Advisors plugin</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-structure leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Advisors scored 96%. Baseline scored 45%. 60 grading runs, zero parse failures.
            </p>
            <p class="text-base text-muted">
              <a href="https://github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins/blob/main/advisors/evals/README.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">Evaluation framework and method (README)</a>
            </p>
          </Card>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- §5 Multi-instance ownership -->
  <section class="section-spacing">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-4">Multi-instance ownership for parallel agents</h2>

        <Card variant="bordered" class="border-l-4 border-l-accent mb-6">
          <p class="text-base text-structure">
            Built on Steve Yegge's <a href="https://github.com/steveyegge/beads" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">Beads</a> and <a href="https://www.dolthub.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">Dolt</a>.
          </p>
        </Card>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-base text-structure leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
          <p>
            Each Claude instance takes a branch-scoped identity and claims work atomically against a shared issue tracker. Claims fail fast when another instance already owns the work. Ownership persists through context compaction and survives session restarts. An issue stays claimed until the branch merges.
          </p>
          <p>
            The pattern generalizes. Any agent harness coordinating multiple workers on parallel, durable work against a shared state store can adopt the same claim and release lifecycle.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- §6 MCP server fluency -->
  <section class="section-spacing bg-foundation-deep">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-4">MCP server fluency</h2>
        <p class="text-base text-muted mb-8 max-w-3xl">
          MCP servers running in production.
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-3">
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">Docling:</strong> DOCX fidelity for document-heavy workflows.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">Playwright:</strong> validates generated UIs before commit.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">Gmail and GitHub:</strong> operational loops against real work queues.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">Anthropic plugins:</strong> first-party integrations for Claude Code skills.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- §7 Foundations -->
  <section class="section-spacing">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-4">Foundations</h2>
        <p class="text-base text-muted mb-8 max-w-3xl">
          Ongoing reading and study.
        </p>

        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-8">
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">DeepLearning.AI Deep Learning Specialization.</strong> Studying.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">3Blue1Brown.</strong> Linear algebra and calculus underpinning LLMs.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">Andrej Karpathy, "Neural Networks: Zero to Hero."</strong> makemore, micrograd, nanoGPT.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">MIT OpenCourseWare.</strong></span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span><strong class="font-medium">Anthropic Discord; invite-only agentskills.io Discord.</strong> Invited by Anthropic team members. Community focused on portable open-source agent skills compatible across agentic harnesses.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-base text-structure leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
          <strong class="font-medium">Changelog-driven adoption.</strong> Features from the Claude changelog (hooks, subagents, plugins, Docling MCP) enter production within weeks of release.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- §8 Published work -->
  <section class="section-spacing bg-foundation-deep">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-h2 font-heading font-semibold text-structure mb-8">Published work</h2>

        <ul class="space-y-3">
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span>
              <a href="https://github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins</a>.
              Portable skills conforming to the agentskills.io specification.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span>
              <a href="https://github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins/tree/main/advisors" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">backchain-plugins/advisors</a>.
              Multi-perspective evaluation plugin.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="text-base text-structure flex items-start">
            <span class="text-accent mr-3 flex-shrink-0">•</span>
            <span>
              <a href="https://github.com/backchainai/backchain-plugins/blob/main/advisors/evals/README.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-structure underline">advisors/evals/README.md</a>.
              Open-source evaluation framework.
            </span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
